king about how Scala interacts with Java during compilation. Usually, the Scala plugin compiles Java alongside it, but just to be safe, I might want to include a holder in the Scala class with `@scala.annotation.meta.field`. I'm not entirely clear if Scala can have public fields without accessor methods. Maybe I should tweak the build.gradle file and ensure that my class and tests align better, especially since the user wants a one-to-one mapping. Should I remove placeholders if they're unrelated?\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Deciding on codec and placeholders**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering whether to update to a basic codec, but that might complicate things. Maybe it's best to leave the existing setup as is. I worry that reviewers might dislike placeholders. The task is to improve coverage for active tests, and I could potentially remove placeholders if there are no test methods. If I leave them, maybe turning the placeholder into a small sanity test would help. However, it’s crucial to ensure that I don't break anything in the process. Reading through metadata might provide the needed support.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_N30ykxQ2KLOgHnzNh2yQUNkn|fc_05db16ac799a99ce0169f8817492e4819c978d524fa78488b4\", \"name\": \"read\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"metadata/com.github.plokhotnyuk.jsoniter-scala/jsoniter-scala-macros_3/2.33.3/reachability-metadata.json\", \"limit\": 200}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 196, \"output\": 1457, \"cacheRead\": 34304, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 35957, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1777893727794, \"responseId\": \"resp_05db16ac799a99ce0169f881603e08819c96cc88f1a4830ffd\"}}\n2269:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**